      <h3>ELI5</h3>
      <p>
        Geophysics is like a big game of "guess what's inside the Earth!"
        Scientists use special tools to measure things like earthquakes,
        magnetic fields, and heat to help them understand what the Earth is made
        of and what's going on inside.
      </p>
      <p>
        It's kind of like when you play "guess what's in the box" by shaking it,
        listening to it, or feeling it. But instead of a box, geophysicists are
        trying to guess what's inside the Earth!
      </p>
      <p>
        With the help of geophysics, scientists have been able to make pictures
        of what's inside the Earth, kind of like taking an X-ray of your body at
        the doctor's office. These pictures help us understand things like
        earthquakes, volcanoes, and even how the Earth's magnetic field works.
      </p>
      <h3>Layman's terms 1</h3>
      <p>
        Geophysics is the study of the physical properties and processes of the
        Earth and other planets. It is a branch of science that uses physics and
        mathematics to understand the Earth's structure, composition, and
        dynamics.
      </p>
      <p>
        Geophysicists study a wide range of phenomena, from the behavior of
        seismic waves during earthquakes to the way magnetic fields are
        generated in the Earth's core. They use a variety of techniques,
        including seismic imaging, gravity measurements, and electromagnetic
        surveys, to collect data about the Earth's interior and surface.
      </p>
      <p>
        The information collected through geophysics can be used to better
        understand natural hazards like earthquakes and volcanoes, as well as to
        explore for natural resources like oil, gas, and minerals. It can also
        help us to understand the evolution of the Earth over time and its place
        in the larger universe.
      </p>
      <h3>Layman's terms 2</h3>
      <p>
        Geophysics is a branch of science that deals with the physical
        properties and processes of the Earth, including its atmosphere, oceans,
        and interior. It involves the application of physics and mathematics to
        study the structure, composition, and behavior of the Earth and its
        components.
      </p>
      <p>
        For example, geophysicists use seismic waves to study the Earth's
        interior and identify the location and magnitude of earthquakes. They
        also use magnetic and gravity measurements to study the Earth's magnetic
        field and map its structure.
      </p>
      <p>
        A verifiable fact is that geophysics has contributed significantly to
        our understanding of the Earth's evolution and the processes that shape
        its surface. For instance, geophysical studies have shown that the
        Earth's crust is made up of tectonic plates that move and interact with
        each other, leading to the formation of mountains, volcanoes, and other
        geological features.
      </p>
      <p>
        In analogy, geophysics is like a doctor who uses various tools and
        techniques to diagnose the health of a patient. Similarly, geophysicists
        use different methods to investigate the Earth's physical properties and
        processes to understand its past, present, and future.
      </p>
